@Marianne Erni Organizations like ACLU are capable of providing documentation to cases as an independent party. They attempted to do so in this case but were rejected. Besides that however, them not being a part of the case is irrelevant because they were subpoenaed for information which means that they legally have to provide information related to the case, if they have it. A person that isn't a party to a case can be subpoenaed for information. It creates a legal obligation to provide information. 
The defenses to a subpoena are that it's irrelevant to the case at hand, and is too intrusive. Both of those defenses are stances that the ACLU can no longer take.
Ignoring a subpoena by not providing the information you have can lead to legal issues, because it is illegal.

